<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[155,794,163,743]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[179,313,303,325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis box="[179,313,303,325]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Solanum sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lam." authorityName="Lam." box="[587,763,303,325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyrifolium">
<emphasis box="[587,699,303,325]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. pyrifolium</emphasis>
Lam.
</taxonomicName>
of Hispaniola, but differs from that species in its more broadly triangular inflorescence outline (
<figureCitation box="[491,571,359,381]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="6.[155,220,1191,1210]" captionTargetBox="[161,999,168,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-447@6.[155,1006,162,1158]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 5. Solanum sousae. A) portion of stem with flowering inflorescence, B) flower, C) flower cross section, D) anthers, E) portion of stem with fruiting inflorecence. A–D drawn from Ventura 2212, E from Maya J. 3938. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0010502.g005" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517453" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517453/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
), minute calyx lobes without thickened margins (
<figureCitation box="[425,493,387,409]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="6.[155,220,1191,1210]" captionTargetBox="[161,999,168,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-447@6.[155,1006,162,1158]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 5. Solanum sousae. A) portion of stem with flowering inflorescence, B) flower, C) flower cross section, D) anthers, E) portion of stem with fruiting inflorecence. A–D drawn from Ventura 2212, E from Maya J. 3938. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0010502.g005" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517453" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517453/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
) and in its lack of a prominent submarginal leaf vein. The leaf pubescence of the two species is very similar, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[321,396,442,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis box="[321,396,442,464]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in general more densely pubescent on the new growth and abaxial corolla surfaces. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[597,726,470,492]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis box="[597,726,470,492]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Solanum sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the more common and sympatric 
<taxonomicName authority="Poir." authorityName="Poir." box="[544,738,498,520]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dulcamaroides">
<emphasis box="[544,684,498,520]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. dulcamaroides</emphasis>
Poir.
</taxonomicName>
in its white flowers, generally simple pubescence (versus more commonly dendritic in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Poir." box="[304,445,553,575]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dulcamaroides">
<emphasis box="[304,445,553,575]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. dulcamaroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), white rather than purple flowers, and in its anthers that are not markedly thickened and rounded abaxially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[155,794,163,743]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
It is likely that the juvenile leaves of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[543,619,637,659]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis box="[543,619,637,659]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are pinnatifid, as are those of most other species in this group; young foliage is only very rarely collected and is often not associated with the flowering stems with simple leaves.
</paragraph>
